# Contech Context SMFS Retrieval

Use this always-on rule when a coding agent may need grounded evidence
from a private construction or engineering corpus.

## Boundary

- Codex owns decomposition and synthesis.
- SMFS provides a local mounted corpus with semantic search.
- Container access is repo-owned in `contech-context.lock`.
- Fresh installs allow/default `structural-engineering-corpora`.
- The default container is a prototype corpus currently centered on notes
  related to concrete design to Eurocode 2 (EC2).
- Use `contech-context smfs-mount --repo .` to mount the installed default
  container in the common path.
- Use `contech-context use <container-tag> --repo .` to add/default and
  mount a different container.
- Use `contech-context containers mount-path <path> --repo .` to persist a
  non-default mount path, and use `contech-context containers smfs-home
  /tmp/h --repo .` when a long container tag needs a shorter SMFS socket
  home on macOS.
- Mount one container per task unless the human explicitly asks for more.
- Mount only containers allowed by the lock.
- Read `<mount>/profile.md` before detailed searching. `<mount>` is the
  `smfs.mount_path` value in `contech-context.lock`; default examples use
  `./memory/mount`, but custom mounts such as `./m` must use the actual
  lock path. `contech-context smfs-mount` publishes a repo-root `.smfs`
  marker so `smfs grep "<query>" <mount>` works from the repo root.
- Use native `smfs grep` against the mounted SMFS path as the first search,
  either by changing into the mount first or by passing the configured mount
  path as the optional command argument.
- Treat `smfs.smfs_home` as mount/setup metadata. Keep normal lookup as
  `smfs grep "<query>" <mount>` unless troubleshooting a native SMFS home
  issue.
- Do not use a contech-context grep wrapper or hosted retrieval path.

## Decomposition

Codex breaks engineering questions into focused evidence needs, sequences the
SMFS lookups, and synthesizes the answer. SMFS only returns mounted corpus
evidence; do not use hosted retrieval or wrapper commands for decomposition.

- Treat retrieval budgets as hard stops: direct lookup and yes/no trap
  questions get at most two focused semantic greps and three shell
  commands total; cross-chapter synthesis gets 3-6 focused semantic
  greps and at most three shell commands total. Batch several bounded
  `smfs grep` pipelines in one shell command when that keeps the workflow
  compact. For each relevant chapter, copy the most specific exact
  heading title from the profile or digest into a grep query, then add
  the question's key symbols or terms. When a question compares concepts
  or says something is useful "again", cite one baseline paragraph for
  the original concept and one paragraph for the new combined-case
  concept. When batching, pass the mount path to each native grep:
  `{ smfs grep "<query1>" <mount> | sed -n "1,80p"; smfs grep "<query2>" <mount> | sed -n "1,80p"; }`.
  If cross-chapter greps return relevant text but no visible paragraph
  refs for a required concept, use the final command for one scoped
  literal fallback on exact visible wording:
  `cd <mount> && rg -n "<exact visible phrase|symbol>" . | sed -n "1,40p"`.
  After the budget is spent, answer from visible paragraph-backed evidence
  or abstain.
- Avoid `pwd`, `ls`, repeated broad semantic searches, broad `rg`, and
  repository-wide scans during corpus retrieval.
- Do not use `rg`, `grep`, `find`, or built-in search inside the mount
  before semantic grep.
- After semantic grep, inspect returned files and nearby lines literally
  only when SMFS returns real paths. Do not construct paths from digest
  filenames.
- If the first semantic grep returns only `(unknown)` snippets with no
  visible paragraph refs for an answerable question, run one exact
  follow-up native `smfs grep` plus one scoped literal fallback in the same
  final command:
  `{ smfs grep "<exact visible phrase|symbol>" <mount> | sed -n "1,80p"; cd <mount> && rg -n "<exact visible phrase|symbol>" . | sed -n "1,40p"; }`.
  Then cite visible paragraph refs or real returned path/line evidence
  from the mount, or abstain.
- For unsupported or corpus-scope questions, read `profile.md`, run one
  focused semantic grep, and default to abstention unless that one grep
  returns direct paragraph-backed support for the exact requested topic.
  Do not run synonym searches, second greps, `rg`, `find`, or broad
  source inspection just to prove absence.
- Cite only visible paragraph refs copied from SMFS output or returned
  files. Treat `(unknown)` snippets and generated memories without
  visible refs as routing hints only.
- When a chunk contains a heading ref and later sentence/formula refs,
  cite the ref immediately attached to the sentence or formula you use,
  not the section heading ref.
- Every substantive answer sentence, including the first yes/no
  correction sentence, must include an inline paragraph ref.
- Before finalizing, perform a citation self-check: each substantive
  sentence has at least one inline ref; each inline ref appears as a
  `References:` bullet; each bullet contains an exact quote copied from
  visible retrieved output; and no bullet is left unused. Delete or
  rewrite any sentence, inline ref, or reference bullet that fails this
  check.
- Preserve exact engineering symbols from evidence, for example
  `V_{Rd,c}`, `M_{tmax}`, `b_e`, `f_{ck}`, `\gamma_c`, and `d`.
- Use standard EC2 notation `V_{Rd,c}` for shear resistance of members
  without shear reinforcement, even if source text has OCR/case variants
  such as `v_{Rd,C}`.
- Format formulas with readable multiplication spacing, for example
  `0.17 b_e f_{ck} d^2` instead of compressed `0.17b_ef_{ck}d^2`.
- If the question names a symbol, repeat that exact symbol in the
  corrected answer.
- Define non-obvious formula symbols when evidence gives definitions. If
  using `b_e`, include the effective-width context such as edge or
  corner column geometry when the corpus distinguishes them, and include
  multiple cases when the corpus defines multiple cases for the symbol.
  For flat-slab `b_e`, look for and report both edge and corner
  effective-width cases when present. Include the corner-column case as
  well as the edge-column case when evidence distinguishes both.
- For yes/no trap questions, answer with explicit `Yes` or `No`, the
  corrected value or location, and one disambiguating detail about any
  false alternative named in the question.
- Treat returned source files and `/profile.md` as valid evidence, but
  label the source type. Unanchored generated-memory snippets are routing
  hints only.
- If evidence is missing or unsupported, abstain or ask a narrower
  question.
- Keep API keys and private corpus extracts out of committed files.

## Default commands

```bash
contech-context smfs-mount --repo .
cat ./memory/mount/profile.md
smfs grep "Focused construction or engineering question" ./memory/mount
```

When `smfs.mount_path` is not `./memory/mount`, substitute that configured
mount path.
